---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import PixelArtHeader from '../components/PixelArtHeader.astro';
import P5Background from '../components/P5Background.astro';
---

<Layout title="SLASHER STATS: The Data Behind the Masks">
	<P5Background />
	
	<main>
		<PixelArtHeader />

		<!-- Introduction -->
		<section class="intro-section">
			<div class="container">
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">TWO ICONS. ONE LEGACY.</h2>
					<p class="body-text">
						In 1978, a masked figure stalked the streets of Haddonfield, Illinois. 
						Two years later, a drowned boy returned from the depths of Crystal Lake. 
						These weren't just horror movies—they were cultural phenomena that would 
						define a generation and spawn franchises spanning over four decades.
					</p>
					<p class="body-text">
						Michael Myers and Jason Voorhees became more than characters. They became 
						icons of fear, symbols of unstoppable evil, and surprisingly, generators 
						of massive box office revenue. But who truly reigns supreme in the pantheon 
						of slasher cinema?
					</p>
					<p class="body-text">
						Let's dive into the data.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Character Introductions -->
		<section class="character-intro">
			<div class="container">
				<div class="character-cards">
					<div class="character-card myers-card" id="myers-card">
						<div class="card-header">
							<h3 class="pixel-text">MICHAEL MYERS</h3>
							<span class="franchise-tag">HALLOWEEN</span>
						</div>
						<div class="card-body">
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">FIRST KILL:</span>
								<span class="value">1978</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">TOTAL FILMS:</span>
								<span class="value">12</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">ESTIMATED KILLS:</span>
								<span class="value">166</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">WEAPON:</span>
								<span class="value">CHEF'S KNIFE</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">LOCATION:</span>
								<span class="value">HADDONFIELD, IL</span>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="pixel-border"></div>
					</div>

					<div class="character-card jason-card" id="jason-card">
						<div class="card-header">
							<h3 class="pixel-text">JASON VOORHEES</h3>
							<span class="franchise-tag">FRIDAY THE 13TH</span>
						</div>
						<div class="card-body">
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">FIRST KILL:</span>
								<span class="value">1981</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">TOTAL FILMS:</span>
								<span class="value">12</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">ESTIMATED KILLS:</span>
								<span class="value">170</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">WEAPON:</span>
								<span class="value">MACHETE</span>
							</div>
							<div class="character-stat">
								<span class="label">LOCATION:</span>
								<span class="value">CRYSTAL LAKE, NJ</span>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="pixel-border"></div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Kill Count Visualization -->
		<section class="data-viz-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">THE BODY COUNT</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						Every slasher film follows a formula: teenagers make poor decisions, 
						and the killer makes them pay. But how do our two icons compare when 
						it comes to their signature metric?
					</p>
				</div>
				
				<!-- Head-to-Head Kill Count Display -->
				<div class="kill-count-showdown">
					<div class="killer-count-card michael-card">
						<div class="killer-name pixel-text">MICHAEL MYERS</div>
						<div class="kill-counter" id="michaelKillCount">0</div>
						<div class="kill-label">TOTAL KILLS</div>
						<div class="kill-stats">
							<div class="kill-stat-item">
								<span class="stat-label">AVG PER FILM:</span>
								<span class="stat-value">13.8</span>
							</div>
							<div class="kill-stat-item">
								<span class="stat-label">DEADLIEST FILM:</span>
								<span class="stat-value">27 (Halloween Kills)</span>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
					
					<div class="vs-badge">
						<div class="vs-text pixel-text">VS</div>
						<div class="difference-text">+4 KILLS</div>
					</div>
					
					<div class="killer-count-card jason-card">
						<div class="killer-name pixel-text">JASON VOORHEES</div>
						<div class="kill-counter winner" id="jasonKillCount">0</div>
						<div class="kill-label">TOTAL KILLS</div>
						<div class="kill-stats">
							<div class="kill-stat-item">
								<span class="stat-label">AVG PER FILM:</span>
								<span class="stat-value">17.0</span>
							</div>
							<div class="kill-stat-item">
								<span class="stat-label">DEADLIEST FILM:</span>
								<span class="stat-value">28 (Jason X)</span>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				
				<div class="insight-box">
					<p class="pixel-text">Jason edges out Michael with 170 total kills vs 166, 
					but the story gets more interesting when we look at kills per film...</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Timeline Visualization -->
		<section class="timeline-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">// FRANCHISE TIMELINE //</h2>
				<div class="timeline">
					<div class="timeline-line"></div>
					
					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div class="timeline-content left">
							<h3>HALLOWEEN (1978)</h3>
							<p>Michael Myers debuts with 5 kills. Budget: $325K → Box Office: $70M. An instant horror classic with 96% on Rotten Tomatoes.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-year">1978</div>
						<div></div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div></div>
						<div class="timeline-year">1980</div>
						<div class="timeline-content right">
							<h3>FRIDAY THE 13TH (1980)</h3>
							<p>Jason's franchise begins (though Pamela is the killer). Budget: $550K → Box Office: $59.8M. A slasher phenomenon is born.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div class="timeline-content left">
							<h3>HALLOWEEN II (1981)</h3>
							<p>Michael returns with 9 kills. Continues directly from the first film's events.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-year">1981</div>
						<div></div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div></div>
						<div class="timeline-year">1981</div>
						<div class="timeline-content right">
							<h3>FRIDAY 13TH PART 2</h3>
							<p>Jason finally takes center stage as the killer with 9 kills. The machete legend begins.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div class="timeline-content left">
							<h3>THE GOLDEN AGE</h3>
							<p>1982-1989: Both franchises dominate the 80s with multiple sequels. Jason releases 5 films, Michael releases 3.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-year">1980s</div>
						<div></div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div></div>
						<div class="timeline-year">2001</div>
						<div class="timeline-content right">
							<h3>JASON X</h3>
							<p>Jason's deadliest film with 28 kills. Jason goes to space in the year 2455.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div class="timeline-content left">
							<h3>HALLOWEEN (2018)</h3>
							<p>Michael's comeback. Budget: $10M → Box Office: $255M. The highest-grossing Halloween film.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-year">2018</div>
						<div></div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item">
						<div></div>
						<div class="timeline-year">2021</div>
						<div class="timeline-content right">
							<h3>HALLOWEEN KILLS</h3>
							<p>Michael's most brutal outing with 27 kills in a single film. Pure carnage.</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Box Office Performance -->
		<section class="data-viz-section dark-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">MONEY & MAYHEM</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						Horror movies are notoriously profitable. Low budgets, massive returns. 
						But which franchise proved more lucrative for the studios?
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="viz-container">
					<canvas id="boxOfficeChart"></canvas>
				</div>
				<div class="comparison-stats">
					<div class="comparison-stat">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">HALLOWEEN</h3>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">Total Box Office:</span>
							<span class="value orange-text">$903.6M</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">Total Budget:</span>
							<span class="value">$113.8M</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">ROI:</span>
							<span class="value orange-text">694%</span>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="comparison-stat">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">FRIDAY THE 13TH</h3>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">Total Box Office:</span>
							<span class="value orange-text">$691.5M</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">Total Budget:</span>
							<span class="value">$95.6M</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat-detail">
							<span class="label">ROI:</span>
							<span class="value orange-text">624%</span>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Critical Reception -->
		<section class="data-viz-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">CRITICS VS. CARNAGE</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						Slasher films have never been critical darlings. But some entries 
						transcended the genre. Let's see how the critics scored each film.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="viz-container">
					<canvas id="criticsChart"></canvas>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Interactive Kill Methods -->
		<section class="interactive-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">TOOLS OF THE TRADE</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						Every killer has their signature. Michael prefers the intimacy of 
						a chef's knife. Jason favors his iconic machete. But both have 
						shown remarkable creativity with their methods.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="weapons-display">
					<div class="weapon-showcase myers-weapons">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">MICHAEL'S ARSENAL</h3>
						<div class="weapon-stat">
							<span class="stat-label">Unique Weapons:</span>
							<span class="stat-value">15</span>
						</div>
						<ul class="weapon-list">
							<li>Chef's Knife (Primary)</li>
							<li>Strangulation / Neck-snapping</li>
							<li>Impaling on objects</li>
							<li>Head crushing (bare hands)</li>
							<li>Blunt instruments</li>
							<li>Environmental objects</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
					<div class="weapon-showcase jason-weapons">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">JASON'S ARSENAL</h3>
						<div class="weapon-stat">
							<span class="stat-label">Unique Weapons:</span>
							<span class="stat-value">25</span>
						</div>
						<p class="body-text">
							Jason has used everything from his signature machete to 
							sleeping bags, harpoon guns, and even liquid nitrogen. 
							His creativity knows no bounds.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Peak Performance -->
		<section class="data-viz-section dark-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">PEAK PERFORMANCE</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						Every franchise has its high point—the film where everything 
						came together (or fell spectacularly apart). Let's look at 
						the extremes.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="peak-stats">
					<div class="peak-card">
						<h3 class="pixel-text orange-text">MOST KILLS (SINGLE FILM)</h3>
						<div class="peak-comparison">
							<div class="peak-item">
								<span class="franchise">HALLOWEEN</span>
								<span class="peak-value">27</span>
								<span class="film-name">Halloween Kills (2021)</span>
							</div>
							<div class="peak-item winner">
								<span class="franchise">FRIDAY THE 13TH</span>
								<span class="peak-value">28</span>
								<span class="film-name">Jason X (2001)</span>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="peak-card">
						<h3 class="pixel-text orange-text">HIGHEST BOX OFFICE</h3>
						<div class="peak-comparison">
							<div class="peak-item winner">
								<span class="franchise">HALLOWEEN</span>
								<span class="peak-value">$255.5M</span>
								<span class="film-name">Halloween (2018)</span>
							</div>
							<div class="peak-item">
								<span class="franchise">FRIDAY THE 13TH</span>
								<span class="peak-value">$116.6M</span>
								<span class="film-name">Freddy vs. Jason (2003)</span>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Scrollytelling Section -->
		<section class="scrolly-section">
			<div class="scrolly-container">
				<div class="scrolly-graphic">
					<canvas id="scrollyCanvas"></canvas>
				</div>
				<div class="scrolly-text">
					<div class="step" data-step="0">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">THE FIRST KILL</h3>
						<p>Michael Myers made his debut in 1978 with just 5 kills. 
						The film cost $325,000 and made $70 million—a staggering 
						21,438% return on investment.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="step" data-step="1">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">JASON RISES</h3>
						<p>Jason didn't actually kill anyone in the first Friday the 13th 
						(that was his mother). He took over in Part 2 (1981) with 9 kills 
						and never looked back.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="step" data-step="2">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">THE GOLDEN AGE</h3>
						<p>The 1980s saw both franchises at their peak output. Between 
						1980-1989, there were 9 Friday the 13th films and 4 Halloween films.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="step" data-step="3">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">MODERN REVIVALS</h3>
						<p>The 2018 Halloween reboot proved there's still massive appetite 
						for these franchises, earning more than the entire original trilogy 
						combined (adjusted for inflation).</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Final Comparison -->
		<section class="final-section">
			<div class="container">
				<h2 class="section-title pixel-text">THE VERDICT</h2>
				<div class="narrative-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						So who wins? Like any good horror franchise, it depends on 
						how you measure success.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="verdict-grid">
					<div class="verdict-card">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">MICHAEL MYERS WINS:</h3>
						<ul class="verdict-list">
							<li>✓ Total Box Office ($903.6M vs $691.5M)</li>
							<li>✓ Highest Single Film Gross ($255.5M)</li>
							<li>✓ Better Critical Reception (avg)</li>
							<li>✓ More Iconic Original Film</li>
							<li>✓ Better ROI</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
					<div class="verdict-card">
						<h3 class="pixel-text">JASON VOORHEES WINS:</h3>
						<ul class="verdict-list">
							<li>✓ Total Kill Count (170 vs 166)</li>
							<li>✓ Highest Single Film Kills (28)</li>
							<li>✓ More Unique Weapons (25 vs 15)</li>
							<li>✓ Faster Kill Rate (6.5 min vs 7.3 min)</li>
							<li>✓ More Geographical Diversity</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="final-text">
					<p class="body-text">
						In the end, both Michael Myers and Jason Voorhees have earned 
						their places in the horror hall of fame. They've terrified 
						audiences for over 40 years, generated billions in revenue, 
						and created a blueprint that countless imitators have followed.
					</p>
					<p class="body-text">
						The real winners? The fans who keep coming back for more.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Footer -->
		<footer class="footer" id="footer-trigger">
			<div class="container">
				<p class="pixel-text">DATA VISUALIZATION BY <a href="https://www.koraresearchcenter.org/">Kora Research Center</a></p>
				<p class="footer-text">All data sourced from box office records, film databases, and fan wikis.</p>
				<p class="footer-text">Built with Astro, Chart.js, p5.js.</p>
			</div>
		</footer>
	</main>

	<!-- Load Chart.js -->
	<script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@4.4.0/dist/chart.umd.min.js"></script>
</Layout>

<!-- Client-side scripts - Load after Chart.js -->
<script>
	// Import and execute the main script
	import '../script.js';
	
	// Debug log
	console.log('Script loaded, waiting for DOM...');
</script>
